The pseudocode I have implemented covers the same value iteration algorithm as Figure 9.16 in Artificial Intelligence: Foundations of Computational Agents, but differs primarily in its level of detail, structure, and focus on implementation. The textbook version is quite abstract and concise, expressing the update steps using compact operations such as taking the maximum over actions and summing over possible next states. In contrast, my pseudocode expands those operations into explicit loops, making each step of the computation clear and directly translatable into code. I have introduced functions in addition to the initial value iteration_function such as GET_ACTIONS, IS_TERMINAL, and ACTION_VALUE, which separate the algorithm into parts making it easier to implement changes or to alter the code to be used in different ways - rather than changing the whole function, it may be easier to change these smaller chunks. This structure is not present in the textbook example.

Another key difference lies in how the transition and reward functions are represented. The textbook example treats these as abstract mathematical functions and does not specify what structures these are, whereas my pseudocode uses concrete data structures, such as dictionaries mapping states and actions to lists of possible outcomes and rewards. This makes the algorithm more practical for programming but less general in a theoretical sense. Additionally, the stopping condition is more explicitly defined in my pseudocode: it introduces a delta value to measure the largest change in state values during each iteration and stops when this change falls below a specified threshold epsilon. It also includes a max_iterations parameter as a safeguard against non-convergence, neither of which are explicitly defined in the textbook pseudocode.

Furthermore, my pseudocode avoids updating values in place by using a copy (V_new) during each iteration, ensuring that all updates are based on the previous iteration’s values. This is not explicitly shown in the textbook edition. Finally, the extraction of the optimal policy is written out step by step, looping through each state and recomputing action values to select the best action, whereas the textbook presents this more briefly and abstractly. Overall, the textbook provides a very concise, conceptual description of value iteration, while my pseudocode offers a more in-depth, version which may be slightly easier to implement.
